---
// three-tier-dark-mode — Chapter 049 Lesson 3, "Readable in every client".
//
// The point this figure cements: a mail client does exactly ONE of three things
// with dark mode, and you don't get to choose which one a recipient's client
// uses — so you must design for all three. Seeing the SAME message wrecked three
// different ways is what makes "design for all three" visceral, and it motivates
// the head plumbing that follows.
//
// Shape: three small email "cards" side by side (the diagrams index + the lesson
// outline both prefer all-three-at-once over tabs — the comparison IS the point).
// Each card is the SAME simplified email — a logo bar, an <h1>, a line of body
// text, and a brand-colored CTA — rendered under one of the three behaviours.
//
//   1 No transformation  → light card, unchanged (Apple Mail macOS).
//   2 Partial inversion   → surface flipped dark, text light, brand CTA + logo
//                           survive (Gmail iOS).
//   3 Full inversion      → EVERYTHING inverted; the dark-on-white logo becomes a
//                           washed-out negative and the brand CTA hue-shifts to a
//                           colour you never picked (Gmail Android).
//
// Why this is devtools-inspectable (the HTML+CSS USP): the inner email markup is
// authored ONCE with fixed authored colours (white surface, near-black ink, a
// blue brand mark + CTA). Panel 2 swaps only the surface/ink via real CSS. Panel
// 3 wraps that identical card in `filter: invert(1) hue-rotate(180deg)` — which
// is, close enough, the actual transform a full-inversion client applies. So the
// negative logo and the hue-shifted CTA aren't hand-picked "wrong" colours; they
// are what the filter genuinely produces from the SAME authored card. A reader
// can open devtools, read the filter, and see the mechanism.
//
// Authored colours are intentionally HARD-CODED (not Starlight theme variables):
// the whole lesson is about what happens to a FIXED set of authored colours under
// each client behaviour, so they must look identical regardless of the page's
// light/dark theme. Only the Figure chrome (labels, panel frames) is theme-aware.
//
// Engine: plain HTML + CSS (the diagrams index's pick for "layout concept
// rendered with real CSS, devtools-inspectable"). `.not-content` drops Starlight
// prose styling. Three columns on a wide Figure; below ~720px they wrap, and the
// inner cards keep a fixed look so the comparison survives. <Figure> + caption
// are supplied by the MDX, not here.

const ALT =
  'The same welcome email rendered under three mail-client dark-mode behaviours. Left, no transformation: a white card with dark text, a blue brand logo, and a blue Verify button, as authored. Middle, partial inversion: the background is now dark and the text light, but the blue logo and blue Verify button are preserved and legible. Right, full inversion: the whole card is inverted, so the logo has become a washed-out light negative on dark and the Verify button has hue-shifted to a wrong orange-brown colour the designer never chose.';

// One authored email card, reused three times. The only difference between the
// three panels is the *treatment* wrapper class, so the comparison is honest.
const tiers = [
  {
    key: 'none',
    n: '1',
    title: 'No transformation',
    client: 'Apple Mail · macOS',
    verdict: 'ok',
    verdictLabel: 'Renders as authored',
  },
  {
    key: 'partial',
    n: '2',
    title: 'Partial inversion',
    client: 'Gmail · iOS',
    verdict: 'ok',
    verdictLabel: 'Brand + logo survive',
  },
  {
    key: 'full',
    n: '3',
    title: 'Full inversion',
    client: 'Gmail · Android',
    verdict: 'bad',
    verdictLabel: 'Logo negative · CTA hue-shifts',
  },
] as const;
---

<div class="ttd not-content" role="img" aria-label={ALT}>
  {
    tiers.map((tier) => (
      <div class="ttd-col">
        {/* Behaviour label + representative client, above each panel. */}
        <div class="ttd-head">
          <span class="ttd-step" aria-hidden="true">
            {tier.n}
          </span>
          <span class="ttd-head-text">
            <span class="ttd-title">{tier.title}</span>
            <span class="ttd-client">{tier.client}</span>
          </span>
        </div>

        {/* The mail-client window. `ttd-mode-*` applies the transform. */}
        <div class={`ttd-frame ttd-mode-${tier.key}`}>
          <div class="ttd-card">
            {/* Logo bar: a brand mark + wordmark, dark-on-white as authored. */}
            <div class="ttd-logo">
              <span class="ttd-mark" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span class="ttd-wordmark">YourApp</span>
            </div>

            <div class="ttd-h1">Verify your email</div>
            <div class="ttd-body">
              Confirm your email so we can finish setting up your account.
            </div>

            <span class="ttd-cta">Verify your email</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* One-line verdict under the panel. */}
        <div class={`ttd-verdict ttd-verdict-${tier.verdict}`}>
          <span class="ttd-verdict-dot" aria-hidden="true" />
          <span>{tier.verdictLabel}</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))
  }
</div>

<style>
  .ttd {
    margin: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: flex-start;
    justify-content: center;
    column-gap: 18px;
    row-gap: 24px;
    font-family: var(--sl-font-system, ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif);
  }
  .ttd * {
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  /* ── A column: head label + the client window + a verdict ──────────────── */
  .ttd-col {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    width: 220px;
  }

  /* ── The behaviour label above each panel (theme-aware chrome) ─────────── */
  .ttd-head {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    min-height: 34px;
  }
  .ttd-step {
    margin: 0;
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 22px;
    height: 22px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1;
    color: var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--sl-color-text-accent, #4f46e5) 16%, var(--sl-color-bg, #fff));
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--sl-color-text-accent, #4f46e5) 45%, transparent);
  }
  .ttd-head-text {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1px;
  }
  .ttd-title {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 13.5px;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.2;
    color: var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b);
  }
  .ttd-client {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 11px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    color: var(--sl-color-gray-3, #64748b);
  }

  /* ── The client "window" frame (theme-aware chrome around the message) ──── */
  .ttd-frame {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 10px;
    border-radius: 12px;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--sl-color-gray-5, #d0d5dd);
    background: var(--sl-color-bg-sidebar, #f3f4f6);
  }

  /* ── The authored email card ───────────────────────────────────────────────
     HARD-CODED colours on purpose: this is the fixed thing the client transforms.
     White surface, near-black ink, a blue brand mark + a blue CTA. */
  .ttd-card {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 9px;
    padding: 14px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #ffffff;
    color: #18181b;
  }

  .ttd-logo {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 7px;
  }
  /* The brand mark — a blue rounded square. Inverting it is what turns the
     "logo" into a washed-out negative in panel 3, the whole point. */
  .ttd-mark {
    margin: 0;
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    width: 18px;
    height: 18px;
    border-radius: 5px;
    background: #2563eb;
  }
  .ttd-wordmark {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    line-height: 1;
    color: #1d4ed8;
  }

  .ttd-h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.2;
    color: #18181b;
  }
  .ttd-body {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 11.5px;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: #3f3f46;
  }

  /* The brand CTA. Blue fill, white text — what the contrast check protects.
     Under full inversion this hue-shifts to the wrong colour. */
  .ttd-cta {
    margin: 4px 0 0;
    align-self: flex-start;
    padding: 8px 14px;
    border-radius: 7px;
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1;
    color: #ffffff;
    background: #2563eb;
  }

  /* ── Behaviour 1 · No transformation ───────────────────────────────────────
     Nothing changes; the authored card renders as-is. */

  /* ── Behaviour 2 · Partial inversion ───────────────────────────────────────
     The client flips light SURFACES to dark and ink to light, but preserves
     elements it reads as already-saturated/dark — the blue brand mark, the blue
     wordmark, and the blue CTA all survive and stay legible. Modelled by
     overriding only the surface + neutral text, leaving the blues untouched. */
  .ttd-mode-partial .ttd-card {
    background: #1c1c1f;
    color: #f4f4f5;
  }
  .ttd-mode-partial .ttd-h1 {
    color: #f4f4f5;
  }
  .ttd-mode-partial .ttd-body {
    color: #c7c7cc;
  }
  .ttd-mode-partial .ttd-wordmark {
    /* lifted just enough to stay legible on dark, as a real client would */
    color: #60a5fa;
  }
  /* .ttd-mark and .ttd-cta keep their authored blue — brand colours survive. */

  /* ── Behaviour 3 · Full inversion ──────────────────────────────────────────
     The client inverts EVERYTHING. `invert(1) hue-rotate(180deg)` is, close
     enough, the transform a full-inversion client applies (the hue-rotate is its
     attempt to keep photos looking right — and it's exactly why brand colours
     land on a wrong hue). Applied to the UNCHANGED authored card, so the negative
     logo and the hue-shifted CTA are genuinely produced by the filter, not by
     hand-picked colours. Devtools shows the one declaration that does it all. */
  .ttd-mode-full .ttd-card {
    filter: invert(1) hue-rotate(180deg);
  }

  /* ── The per-panel verdict line (theme-aware chrome) ───────────────────── */
  .ttd-verdict {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 7px;
    padding: 0 2px;
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .ttd-verdict-dot {
    margin: 0;
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    width: 9px;
    height: 9px;
    border-radius: 999px;
  }
  .ttd-verdict-ok {
    color: color-mix(in srgb, #16a34a 75%, var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b));
  }
  .ttd-verdict-ok .ttd-verdict-dot {
    background: #16a34a;
  }
  .ttd-verdict-bad {
    color: color-mix(in srgb, #dc2626 78%, var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b));
  }
  .ttd-verdict-bad .ttd-verdict-dot {
    background: #dc2626;
  }
</style>
